        "title": "Java: BASE64Decoder outputs wrong value",
        "body": "<p>I have a problem with decoding text.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have a field in my app:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>JTextArea jCertImport = new JTextArea();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>jCertImport contains BASE64 encoded text.\nI want to decode text inserted in jCertImport, so I can get the byte form before encoding:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>import sun.misc.BASE64Decoder;\nimport sun.misc.BASE64Encoder;\n\n...\n\nbyte [] cert_bin = null;\nBASE64Decoder cert_decoded = new BASE64Decoder();\ntry {\ncert_bin = cert_decoded.decodeBuffer(jCertImport.getText());\n} catch (IOException e) {\n    // TODO Auto-generated catch block\n    e.printStackTrace();\n  }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and after that I get the the byte form of my cert, but the value is different than the one before encoding. Why? I thought, that when I use encode on some value and then decode on the output I should get the oryginal value before encoding.<\/p>\n",
